3.10 DEV CONTAINER USER AND PASSWORDLESS SUDO
     The Dev Container's appuser (the non-root user the agent and
     development services run as) MUST have passwordless sudo baked
     into the image. This prevents permissions issues if the
     container is rebuilt, stopped, or restarted while the agent is
     running unattended. This is a development convenience only - it
     must NEVER carry into production images.

     Required configuration:

     a) .devcontainer/Dockerfile (or the root Dockerfile that the
        Dev Container builds from):
            ARG USERNAME=appuser
            ARG USER_UID=1000
            ARG USER_GID=$USER_UID
            RUN apt-get update \
                && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends sudo \
                && groupadd --gid $USER_GID $USERNAME \
                && useradd --uid $USER_UID --gid $USER_GID -m -s /bin/bash $USERNAME \
                && echo "$USERNAME ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL" \
                   > /etc/sudoers.d/$USERNAME \
                && chmod 0440 /etc/sudoers.d/$USERNAME \
                && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*
            USER $USERNAME

     b) .devcontainer/devcontainer.json:
            {
              "remoteUser": "appuser",
              "containerUser": "appuser",
              "updateRemoteUserUID": true,
              "workspaceFolder": "/workspaces/SHIELD062626"
            }

     c) Ownership of the workspace mount:
            Every path under /workspaces/SHIELD062626 is owned
            by appuser:appuser. If a rebuild creates ownership drift,
            the agent fixes it with:
              sudo chown -R appuser:appuser /workspaces/SHIELD062626

     d) The appuser can run any of these without a password prompt:
            sudo apt-get install <package>
            sudo chown <user>:<group> <path>
            sudo chmod <mode> <path>
            sudo systemctl restart <service>   (if applicable)
            sudo -i                            (interactive root if needed)

     Rationale: The agent runs unattended. A passwordless-sudo setup
     means any container rebuild, restart, or system-package install
     succeeds without prompting. Without this, the agent can hang on
     a sudo password prompt and the whole background run stalls.

     PRODUCTION NOTE (critical): the production runtime Dockerfile
     (separate from .devcontainer/Dockerfile) MUST follow least-
     privilege:
       - No sudo installed in the runtime image.
       - The runtime user has no shell (or /sbin/nologin).
       - The runtime user has only the read/write permissions it
         needs to operate the app.
     Eugene has accepted the development-environment passwordless-
     sudo risk because the dev container is isolated and ephemeral.
     That acceptance does not extend to production images.

3.11 PRE-BUILD PERMISSIONS SETUP (FIX BEFORE BUILDING)
     Before you start the actual build, you must verify and fix
     any permission issues so that no command later in the run
     stalls or fails on EACCES. This is mandatory pre-flight work,
     not an optimization. Run these checks at the very start of
     the autonomous (Phase B) invocation, BEFORE the opening
     commit in Section 8.

     a) Verify the workspace is fully owned by appuser:
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser /workspaces/SHIELD062626
          sudo chmod -R u+rwX /workspaces/SHIELD062626

     b) Verify cache directories are owned by appuser. These are
        common offenders if any package was previously installed
        as root or via a different user:
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.npm 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/pnpm 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/yarn 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/pip 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/poetry 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/uv 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.local 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.config 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/ms-playwright 2>/dev/null || true
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser ~/.cache/Cypress 2>/dev/null || true

     c) If you use a named Docker volume for node_modules (common
        for performance), the volume's mount point will be owned
        by root on first mount. Fix it once after the container
        starts:
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser <node_modules_volume_path>

     d) Ensure the .git directory is owned by appuser. Codespaces
        and some Dev Container setups create it as root:
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser \
            /workspaces/SHIELD062626/.git
        Also configure git to trust the repo path inside the
        container (avoids "dubious ownership" warnings):
          git config --global --add safe.directory \
            /workspaces/SHIELD062626

     e) Create .devcontainer/post-create.sh and post-start.sh
        scripts that automate (a)-(d) on every container create/
        start. Sketch:

          #!/usr/bin/env bash
          # .devcontainer/post-create.sh
          # Runs ONCE after the container is first created.
          set -euo pipefail
          REPO=/workspaces/SHIELD062626
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser "$REPO"
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser \
            ~/.npm ~/.cache ~/.local ~/.config 2>/dev/null || true
          git config --global --add safe.directory "$REPO"
          # Install dependencies once after create:
          (cd "$REPO/apps/web" && pnpm install --frozen-lockfile)
          (cd "$REPO/apps/api" && poetry install)

          #!/usr/bin/env bash
          # .devcontainer/post-start.sh
          # Runs every time the container starts.
          set -euo pipefail
          REPO=/workspaces/SHIELD062626
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser "$REPO"
          sudo chown -R appuser:appuser \
            ~/.npm ~/.cache 2>/dev/null || true

