6. CONSTRAINTS AND FORBIDDEN PATTERNS
================================================================================

These are the v1 mistakes you must NEVER repeat. Spec section 14 has
the full list; the most important are below.

6.1  NEVER expose internal slug or enum values to users. No
     "extraction_review", "Zero_trust intake", "ai_extraction",
     "primary_poc". Map every enum to a friendly display label at
     the API boundary or template-render layer.

6.2  NEVER render raw JSON in any user-facing UI. AI output, lineage
     data, audit log details all render as readable content (tables,
     formatted text, cards). <pre>JSON</pre> is FORBIDDEN in any
     component a non-developer can reach.

6.3  NEVER expose stack traces to end users. Global exception handler
     returns a generic friendly message with a correlation ID. The
     real error logs server-side. Werkzeug-style debug pages are
     disabled in any environment a user can reach.

6.4  NEVER ask for the same data twice. User profile (title, phone)
     lives on User. The Primary POC FK points to a User. Settings
     and intake share the same fields. Pre-populate from the
     authenticated session everywhere possible.

6.5  NEVER pre-populate a form field with a single object's value
     for every column. The v1 "Acme Co everywhere" bug came from
     this. Every save handler MUST validate that field assignments
     come from the matching form key. Write a regression test that
     round-trips a Client through the intake form: create via POST,
     read via the admin route, assert every submitted field matches
     what was submitted.

6.6  NEVER fire a partial service selection. If the client picks
     Zero Trust AND ATT&CK, the handler creates project records for
     BOTH - never just the first one.

6.7  NEVER skip the admin notification on a high-priority event.
     New client signup, intake complete, new message from client,
     failed background job - all MUST dispatch an admin notification.

6.8  NEVER leave a dashboard operationally empty. Every client home
     and every admin queue MUST answer "what should I do next?"
     without requiring drill-down.

6.9  NEVER use the native HTML file input for document upload.
     Always drag-and-drop zone with visual feedback, file list,
     per-file progress, file type hints.

6.10 NEVER design a questionnaire as a single massive scroll.
     Section tabs, progress bar, auto-save on blur, resume
     capability are mandatory.

6.11 NEVER leave a queue, list, or activity feed without timestamps.
     "Waiting since" is operationally critical. Render in the user's
     local timezone (UTC stored, local rendered via <time> + JS
     converter).

6.12 NEVER point the notification bell at the home page. Either
     build /notifications, or hide the bell entirely until it has
     a destination.

6.13 NEVER let an LLM call leave the deployment without passing
     through the redactor. The redactor is the primary data
     protection control under the v1 commercial-AI risk acceptance.
     Every LLM call MUST be audited.

6.14 NEVER hardcode the LLM provider, model name, or API endpoint.
     Configure via environment variables only.

6.15 NEVER inline filename construction in a route handler. Use one
     centralized filename-build function (services/filename.py) for
     every download.

6.16 NEVER ship a Phase complete if any of the spec's acceptance
     criteria for that phase are failing. Document the failure in
     DECISIONS.md and proceed past the phase only if Eugene's review
     later allows it.

6.17 NEVER violate the round 6 design language. Specifically:
     - NO cyberpunk, neon, or "hacker" aesthetics. No matrix-green
       glow, no neon outlines, no synthwave gradients.
     - NO gaming UI patterns, achievement badges, XP bars, or
       playful mascots.
     - NO consumer-style decorative graphics, hero illustrations
       used as ornament, or stock-photo overlays on operational
       screens.
     - NO saturated accent colors except where they convey alert
       state or status (success / warning / error / info).
     - NO emoji as functional UI affordances.
     - NO over-animation. No looping motion. No parallax. No
       distracting transitions.
     - NO dense telemetry on public / external pages.
     - NO technical jargon on landing pages or executive views.
     - NO chart clutter (excess legends, drop shadows, 3D
       perspective, gratuitous gridlines).
     - NO product copy that says "Claude," "the AI," "ChatGPT," or
       names the LLM. Refer to platform analysis features as
       "automated analysis," "SHIELD analysis," or "the analysis
       engine."
     - NO dashboard left operationally empty. Every dashboard
       surfaces something useful on first paint.

